Plotting pie chart¶

In [11]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
data=pd.read_csv("D:\\Internship Progress\\WEEK3 new updated\\WEEK3\\Hospitality\\waiting referesh.csv")
count_positive = 0
count_negative = 0
count_neutral = 0

for sentiment in data['sentiment']:
    if sentiment == 'Positive':
        count_positive += 1
    else:
        count_negative += 1
total=len(data)
positive_response= (count_positive / total) * 100
negative_response = (count_negative / total) * 100
myexplode = [0.2, 0]
y=[positive_response,negative_response]
plt.pie(y,labels=[str(round(positive_response,2))+"%",str(round(negative_response,2))+"%"],explode = myexplode, shadow = True,colors=["g","r"])
plt.title("Hospitality tweet % distribution")
plt.legend(["positive","negative"])
plt.show()

LDA for positive tweets¶

In [12]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation

from sklearn.feature_extraction import text

# Read the positive reviews data
positive_reviews = pd.read_csv("D:\\Internship Progress\\WEEK3 new updated\\WEEK3\\Hospitality\\waiting referesh - Copy.csv")

# Combine reviews into a list
reviews = positive_reviews['tweet'].tolist()

# Create a custom stop words list if needed
custom_stop_words = ["read", "good", "disney", "yorker", "day", "didn", "stay", "great", "check", "booked", "like", "die", "told", "friendly", "clean", "sehr", "das", "zimmer", "und", "nice", "did", "was", "really", "safe", "walk", "close", "got"]

# Add your custom stop words to this list
stop_words = text.ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS.union(custom_stop_words)

# Vectorize the text data
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df=0.95, min_df=2, stop_words=stop_words)
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(reviews)

# Apply LDA for topic modeling
num_topics = 5
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components=num_topics, random_state=42)
lda.fit(X)

# Extract top words for each topic
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
topics = []
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    top_words_idx = topic.argsort()[-10:]
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in top_words_idx]
    topics.append(top_words)

# Print the top words for each topic (possible reasons for positive reviews)


for i, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {i + 1}: {', '.join(topic)}")

Topic 1: crew, matter, service, sitting, 20, taxi, passenger, time, people, flight
Topic 2: tickets, normal, trash, learn, snacks, hundreds, blrairport, air, seat, area
Topic 3: taxi, floor, chennai, security, hour, uber, area, minutes, flight, time
Topic 4: layovers, guy, travel, better, fun, flight, lot, air, area, sitting
Topic 5: minutes, care, minimum, said, book, cab, 30, uber, service, time

Observation on positive tweets¶

  • ### There are a number of positive tweets about Bangalore International Airport (BLR).
  • ### The tweets mention that the airport has a friendly and helpful crew, good service, and comfortable seating areas.
  • ### The tweets also mention that the airport has a variety of food and beverage options, and that it is easy to get around. ## Recommendations
  • ### BLR should continue to invest in its crew and training programs to ensure that they are providing excellent service to passengers.
  • ### BLR should also continue to maintain its facilities and amenities to a high standard.
  • ### BLR could consider expanding its food and beverage options, and adding more comfortable seating areas.
  • ### BLR could also consider adding more signage and information points to help passengers find their way around the airport.

Word cloud for positive tweets¶

In [13]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from wordcloud import WordCloud

# Create a word cloud object
wc = WordCloud(background_color="white", max_font_size=50)

# Check the type of the topics variable
if isinstance(topics, list):
    # Convert the topics variable to a list of strings
    topics = [" ".join(topic) for topic in topics]

# Generate the word cloud
wc.generate(" ".join(topics))

# Plot the word cloud
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
plt.imshow(wc)
plt.axis("off")
plt.title("Top Words in Positive Reviews")
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation

from sklearn.feature_extraction import text

# Read the negative reviews data
negative_reviews = pd.read_csv("D:\\Internship Progress\\WEEK3 new updated\\WEEK3\\Hospitality\\waiting referesh - Copy (2).csv")

# Combine reviews into a list
reviews = negative_reviews['tweet'].tolist()

# Create a custom stop words list if needed
custom_stop_words = ["read", "good", "disney", "yorker", "day", "didn", "stay", "great", "check", "booked", "like", "die", "told", "friendly", "clean", "sehr", "das", "zimmer", "und", "nice", "did", "was", "really", "safe", "walk", "close", "got"]

# Add your custom stop words to this list
stop_words = text.ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS.union(custom_stop_words)

# Vectorize the text data
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df=0.95, min_df=2, stop_words=stop_words)
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(reviews)

# Apply LDA for topic modeling
num_topics = 5
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components=num_topics, random_state=42)
lda.fit(X)

# Extract top words for each topic
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
topics = []
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    top_words_idx = topic.argsort()[-10:]
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in top_words_idx]
    topics.append(top_words)

# Print the top words for each topic (possible reasons for positive reviews)


for i, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {i + 1}: {', '.join(topic)}")

Topic 1: queue, indigo6e, t2, experience, long, mins, staff, uber, time, hours
Topic 2: minutes, fancy, matter, inaugurated, remains, flight, bag, problem, t2, 30
Topic 3: taking, cab, passengers, customer, missed, people, flight, worst, akasaair, uber
Topic 4: 10, 40, help, passengers, money, amp, hours, indigo, 20, flight
Topic 5: ola, uber_india, mumbai, delayed, airindia, cabs, pathetic, service, uber, flight

Observation on negative tweets¶

  • ### There are a number of negative tweets about Bangalore International Airport (BLR).
  • ### The tweets mention that the queues are long, the staff is unhelpful, and the overall experience is poor.
  • ### The tweets also mention that flights are often delayed and that it can be difficult to get a taxi or ride-hailing service. ## Recommendations
  • ### BLR should investigate why the queues are so long and take steps to reduce the wait time for passengers.
  • ### BLR should train its staff to be more helpful and responsive to passenger needs.
  • ### BLR should work with airlines to reduce the number of flight delays.
  • ### BLR could consider partnering with taxi and ride-hailing companies to offer discounted rates to passengers.
